    33ŌåÆ/// A value in a key-value.
    34ŌåÆ///
    35ŌåÆ/// Values are an anonymous bag containing some structured datum.
    36ŌåÆ///
    37ŌåÆ/// # Capturing values
    38ŌåÆ///
    39ŌåÆ/// There are a few ways to capture a value:
    40ŌåÆ///
    41ŌåÆ/// - Using the `Value::from_*` methods.
    42ŌåÆ/// - Using the `ToValue` trait.
    43ŌåÆ/// - Using the standard `From` trait.
    44ŌåÆ///
    45ŌåÆ/// ## Using the `Value::from_*` methods
    46ŌåÆ///
    47ŌåÆ/// `Value` offers a few constructor methods that capture values of different kinds.
    48ŌåÆ///
    49ŌåÆ/// ```
    50ŌåÆ/// use log::kv::Value;
    51ŌåÆ///
    52ŌåÆ/// let value = Value::from_debug(&42i32);
    53ŌåÆ///
    54ŌåÆ/// assert_eq!(None, value.to_i64());
    55ŌåÆ/// ```
    56ŌåÆ///
    57ŌåÆ/// ## Using the `ToValue` trait
    58ŌåÆ///
    59ŌåÆ/// The `ToValue` trait can be used to capture values generically.
    60ŌåÆ/// It's the bound used by `Source`.
    61ŌåÆ///
    62ŌåÆ/// ```
    63ŌåÆ/// # use log::kv::ToValue;
    64ŌåÆ/// let value = 42i32.to_value();
    65ŌåÆ///
    66ŌåÆ/// assert_eq!(Some(42), value.to_i64());
    67ŌåÆ/// ```
    68ŌåÆ///
    69ŌåÆ/// ## Using the standard `From` trait
    70ŌåÆ///
    71ŌåÆ/// Standard types that implement `ToValue` also implement `From`.
    72ŌåÆ///
    73ŌåÆ/// ```
    74ŌåÆ/// use log::kv::Value;
    75ŌåÆ///
    76ŌåÆ/// let value = Value::from(42i32);
    77ŌåÆ///
    78ŌåÆ/// assert_eq!(Some(42), value.to_i64());
    79ŌåÆ/// ```
    80ŌåÆ///
    81ŌåÆ/// # Data model
    82ŌåÆ///
    83ŌåÆ/// Values can hold one of a number of types:
    84ŌåÆ///
    85ŌåÆ/// - **Null:** The absence of any other meaningful value. Note that
    86ŌåÆ///   `Some(Value::null())` is not the same as `None`. The former is
    87ŌåÆ///   `null` while the latter is `undefined`. This is important to be
    88ŌåÆ///   able to tell the difference between a key-value that was logged,
    89ŌåÆ///   but its value was empty (`Some(Value::null())`) and a key-value
    90ŌåÆ///   that was never logged at all (`None`).
    91ŌåÆ/// - **Strings:** `str`, `char`.
    92ŌåÆ/// - **Booleans:** `bool`.
    93ŌåÆ/// - **Integers:** `u8`-`u128`, `i8`-`i128`, `NonZero*`.
    94ŌåÆ/// - **Floating point numbers:** `f32`-`f64`.
    95ŌåÆ/// - **Errors:** `dyn (Error + 'static)`.
    96ŌåÆ/// - **`serde`:** Any type in `serde`'s data model.
    97ŌåÆ/// - **`sval`:** Any type in `sval`'s data model.
    98ŌåÆ///
    99ŌåÆ/// # Serialization
   100ŌåÆ///
   101ŌåÆ/// Values provide a number of ways to be serialized.
   102ŌåÆ///
   103ŌåÆ/// For basic types the [`Value::visit`] method can be used to extract the
   104ŌåÆ/// underlying typed value. However, this is limited in the amount of types
   105ŌåÆ/// supported (see the [`VisitValue`] trait methods).
   106ŌåÆ///
   107ŌåÆ/// For more complex types one of the following traits can be used:
   108ŌåÆ///  * `sval::Value`, requires the `kv_sval` feature.
   109ŌåÆ///  * `serde::Serialize`, requires the `kv_serde` feature.
   110ŌåÆ///
   111ŌåÆ/// You don't need a visitor to serialize values through `serde` or `sval`.
   112ŌåÆ///
   113ŌåÆ/// A value can always be serialized using any supported framework, regardless
   114ŌåÆ/// of how it was captured. If, for example, a value was captured using its
   115ŌåÆ/// `Display` implementation, it will serialize through `serde` as a string. If it was
   116ŌåÆ/// captured as a struct using `serde`, it will also serialize as a struct
   117ŌåÆ/// through `sval`, or can be formatted using a `Debug`-compatible representation.
   118ŌåÆ#[derive(Clone)]
   119ŌåÆpub struct Value<'v> {
   120ŌåÆ    inner: inner::Inner<'v>,
   121ŌåÆ}
