   797ŌåÆ///
   798ŌåÆ/// # Use
   799ŌåÆ///
   800ŌåÆ/// `Record` structures are passed as parameters to the [`log`][method.log]
   801ŌåÆ/// method of the [`Log`] trait. Logger implementors manipulate these
   802ŌåÆ/// structures in order to display log messages. `Record`s are automatically
   803ŌåÆ/// created by the [`log!`] macro and so are not seen by log users.
   804ŌåÆ///
   805ŌåÆ/// Note that the [`level()`] and [`target()`] accessors are equivalent to
   806ŌåÆ/// `self.metadata().level()` and `self.metadata().target()` respectively.
   807ŌåÆ/// These methods are provided as a convenience for users of this structure.
   808ŌåÆ///
   809ŌåÆ/// # Example
   810ŌåÆ///
   811ŌåÆ/// The following example shows a simple logger that displays the level,
   812ŌåÆ/// module path, and message of any `Record` that is passed to it.
   813ŌåÆ///
   814ŌåÆ/// ```
   815ŌåÆ/// struct SimpleLogger;
   816ŌåÆ///
   817ŌåÆ/// impl log::Log for SimpleLogger {
   818ŌåÆ///    fn enabled(&self, _metadata: &log::Metadata) -> bool {
   819ŌåÆ///        true
   820ŌåÆ///    }
   821ŌåÆ///
   822ŌåÆ///    fn log(&self, record: &log::Record) {
   823ŌåÆ///        if !self.enabled(record.metadata()) {
   824ŌåÆ///            return;
   825ŌåÆ///        }
   826ŌåÆ///
   827ŌåÆ///        println!("{}:{} -- {}",
   828ŌåÆ///                 record.level(),
   829ŌåÆ///                 record.target(),
   830ŌåÆ///                 record.args());
   831ŌåÆ///    }
   832ŌåÆ///    fn flush(&self) {}
   833ŌåÆ/// }
   834ŌåÆ/// ```
   835ŌåÆ///
   836ŌåÆ/// [method.log]: trait.Log.html#tymethod.log
